# API Design Patterns for JetBrains AI Assistant

## API Design Philosophy
- Design APIs with the consumer in mind
- Follow RESTful principles where appropriate
- Maintain backward compatibility when possible
- Use consistent naming and structure patterns
- Document APIs thoroughly and keep documentation up to date

## Resource Naming Conventions
- Use nouns to represent resources (users, orders, products)
- Use plural nouns for collections (users, not user)
- Use lowercase letters and hyphens for readability
- Use hierarchical paths for relationships (users/{id}/orders)
- Avoid verbs in resource paths

## HTTP Methods Usage
- GET: Retrieve resources (safe, idempotent)
- POST: Create new resources or trigger processes
- PUT: Update entire resources (idempotent)
- PATCH: Partial resource updates
- DELETE: Remove resources (idempotent)

## Response Design
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 404, 500, etc.)
- Provide consistent response structures
- Include meaningful error messages
- Support content negotiation (JSON, XML)
- Use pagination for large collections

## Request Design
- Use query parameters for filtering, sorting, and pagination
- Limit the number of query parameters per endpoint
- Use consistent parameter naming conventions
- Validate input parameters and provide clear error messages
- Support request validation and sanitization

## Versioning Strategy
- Implement API versioning (URL path or headers)
- Maintain backward compatibility when possible
- Deprecate old versions with advance notice
- Document breaking changes clearly
- Use semantic versioning for API versions

## Authentication and Authorization
- Implement secure authentication (OAuth 2.0, API keys, JWT)
- Use HTTPS for all API communications
- Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse
- Include proper authorization checks
- Follow security best practices

## Error Handling
- Use consistent error response format
- Provide meaningful error codes and messages
- Include correlation IDs for debugging
- Document error responses in API specifications
- Log errors appropriately for monitoring

## Performance Considerations
- Implement caching strategies where appropriate
- Use compression for large responses
- Support partial responses (fields selection)
- Implement efficient querying and indexing
- Monitor API performance metrics

## Documentation Standards
- Provide comprehensive API documentation
- Use tools like OpenAPI/Swagger for specification
- Include example requests and responses
- Document authentication and authorization requirements
- Provide SDKs or client libraries when beneficial

## Testing APIs
- Implement comprehensive API testing
- Test both positive and negative scenarios
- Validate response schemas and data formats
- Test authentication and authorization flows
- Monitor API performance and reliability